('REF-00763', 'grey', NULL, 0, 1, 'Koch JP (profiled); Deutsches Architektenblatt',
 2019, 'Deaf Space: Die richtige Architektur für Gehörlose – inklusive Checkliste',
 'Deutsches Architektenblatt (DABonline) — Bundesarchitektenkammer', 'de', 'de', 'manual_native_language_verification',
 3, 'grey', 'DE', NULL, NULL, NULL,
 'AUTHOR-TITLE-ONLY', 'VERIFIED-2', 'https://www.dabonline.de/architektur/deaf-space-die-richtige-architektur-bauen-fuer-gehoerlose-jan-philipp-koch/',
 '[session_2026-07-19-non-english-research-recovery-batch4] FRESH RESEARCH (PRE-REMEDIATION-stub slug). WebFetch non-functional this session. Verified via multiple independent WebSearch passes returning consistent detail (the specific checklist content, the nose-shadow/lip-reading lighting point), published by Deutsches Architektenblatt, the official professional journal of the German Chambers of Architects. Germany has NO binding national standard for Deaf-specific spatial design -- DIN 18040 covers only the general "two-senses principle" (accessibility doctrine, not DeafSpace-style design) and is not cited as a substitute here. A frequently-surfacing "Richtlinien Hörbehindertengerechtes Bauen" document is Swiss (SIA 500:2009 Appendix F), not German -- explicitly NOT conflated with a German source.',
 'Fresh-research recovery per research-handoff-non-english.md, extended to a PRE-REMEDIATION-stub slug (deaf-spatial-design, DE).',
 'Profiles Dr. Jan Philipp Koch, a Deaf German architect, on DeafSpace-specific design applied to his own residence: near-total absence of internal partition walls to preserve sightlines; large glass fronts and glazed corridor corners so approaching people are visible; indirect/diffuse lighting avoiding glare and the "nose-shadow" effect that impairs lip-reading under direct/downward light. A related built exemplar (Elbschule Hamburg, a German school for Deaf/hard-of-hearing students, occupied 2013) applies the same principles (glazed corridor corners, recessed monitors, light-signal systems) but is not separately ingested -- documented here as corroborating context.',
 strftime('%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ','now'), 'session_2026-07-19-non-english-research-recovery-batch4', strftime('%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ','now'), 'session_2026-07-19-non-english-research-recovery-batch4'),

('REF-00764', 'grey', NULL, 0, 1, 'Tsukuba University of Technology (国立大学法人筑波技術大学)',
 2025, '天久保キャンパス (Amakubo Campus) facilities description',
 'Tsukuba University of Technology', 'ja', 'ja', 'manual_native_language_verification',
 3, 'grey', 'JP', NULL, NULL, NULL,
 'AUTHOR-TITLE-ONLY', 'VERIFIED-2', 'https://www.tsukuba-tech.ac.jp/introduction/openinfo/educational_info/amakubo_campus.html',
 '[session_2026-07-19-non-english-research-recovery-batch4] FRESH RESEARCH (PRE-REMEDIATION-stub slug). WebFetch non-functional this session. Verified via the university''s own official site content plus a corroborating June 2025 news item ("デフスペースデザイン講演会を開催" / DeafSpace Design Lecture Held) on the same domain, independently confirmed via two WebSearch queries. Japan also has NO binding national government standard for Deaf-specific spatial design (general バリアフリー法 is accessibility law, not Deaf-spatial-specific, and is not cited as a substitute).',
